04:18.259 --> 04:19.791
We're gonna cut up
this moose quarter.

04:19.827 --> 04:22.628
It's the last one that
we have from the moose we
harvested this past fall.

04:22.663 --> 04:25.664
It's a ham, really
tasty, prime cut piece.

04:25.933 --> 04:27.933
I'll hack the
bone out of here.

04:27.952 --> 04:31.203
Start taking apart
the muscle groups.

04:33.641 --> 04:36.942
<i> NARRATOR: Erik and</i>
<i> Martha Salitan rely on</i>
<i> the animals they hunt,</i>

04:36.977 --> 04:39.678
<i> to maintain a subsistence</i>
<i> lifestyle in the arctic.</i>

04:42.016 --> 04:44.750
ERIK: Oh, you wanna scrap
together a smoker and
smoke some of this meat?

04:44.785 --> 04:47.286
MARTHA MAE: Yeah, that
could be fun, different.

04:47.321 --> 04:49.655
ERIK: Break up the
cuisine a little bit?

04:49.690 --> 04:51.890
MARTHA MAE: Uh-hmm.

04:52.793 --> 04:54.693
Harvesting your own meat,
it's very fulfilling.

04:54.728 --> 04:57.929
You feel a lot better
knowing that you
butchered the animal,

04:58.499 --> 04:59.998
it's all good quality meat,

05:00.034 --> 05:02.567
and it makes you feel a
little bit more independent,
living in the bush.

05:03.704 --> 05:05.037
ERIK: Well, I'm done.

05:05.072 --> 05:07.039
Let's go out and check
out what we got for
building materials.

05:07.074 --> 05:08.640
MARTHA MAE: Sounds good.

05:08.676 --> 05:10.642
I'm done, too.

05:14.648 --> 05:17.316
ERIK: The type of smoker
that we're looking to
make is a cold smoker.

05:17.351 --> 05:19.918
It just adds a little
bit more flavor.

05:19.953 --> 05:21.620
It doesn't add any
nutritional value.

05:21.722 --> 05:24.723
It has nothing to do with
life or death, it's just
a little spice of life.

05:25.693 --> 05:28.193
MARTHA MAE: Doing these
small kind of projects is fun
because it's like a change of

05:28.228 --> 05:31.129
pace, something different
than the daily chores.

05:31.999 --> 05:34.299
ERIK: I'm gonna use these
two by sixes that are left
over from building this

05:34.335 --> 05:36.301
hangar this past summer.

05:36.337 --> 05:39.171
We're gonna go six feet
deep, six feet wide, and put
a six-foot roof on there.

05:40.874 --> 05:43.208
MARTHA MAE: We're putting
up the sheet metal here,
which is not only going to

05:43.243 --> 05:45.744
complete the smokehouse, but
make it sturdier.

05:46.914 --> 05:49.181
ERIK: Feed it up
on the top there.

05:49.216 --> 05:51.083
MARTHA MAE: So far,
progress has been real fast.

05:51.118 --> 05:53.085
We have four walls, we've
got the roofs all ready.

05:53.120 --> 05:55.454
We've pounded it out and
we're just gonna keep moving.

05:56.090 --> 05:58.223
Is it gonna fit?

05:59.159 --> 06:02.361
ERIK: We're gonna get this
door on hinges, make sure
it flows the way we want it.

06:02.396 --> 06:04.229
Then we'll sheet
the son of a gun.

06:04.264 --> 06:06.732
MARTHA MAE: It's nice
to be able to work on our
own little projects at

06:06.767 --> 06:10.402
our own pace and
do what we wanna do.

06:15.876 --> 06:18.110
Nice.

06:18.145 --> 06:19.244
ERIK: And it's solid.

06:19.279 --> 06:20.846
MARTHA MAE: Yeah.

06:20.881 --> 06:23.849
ERIK: And the first moose
we smoke in there is the
moose that antlers it is.

06:23.884 --> 06:28.186
I'm just pumped to drag
it out of here and fire
it up for the first time.

06:29.623 --> 06:32.190
CHIP: There's only so much
you can talk about to your
kids and there's only so many

06:32.226 --> 06:33.892
stories that they can
read and see and hear.

06:33.927 --> 06:36.428
The best you can do is just
take them out there with you.

06:45.439 --> 06:48.473
AGNES: It's about to come up
right in front of you, Carol.

06:49.109 --> 06:50.308
Yee!

06:50.344 --> 06:52.944
CHIP: Good one.
AGNES: Good shot.
CAROL: This is fun.

06:54.114 --> 06:55.747
<i> NARRATOR: For the Hailstones,</i>

06:55.783 --> 06:59.418
<i> it's critical for everyone</i>
<i> to do their part to harvest</i>
<i> muskrat meat and fur.</i>

06:59.453 --> 07:02.888
<i> The window for the hunt</i>
<i> is brief, as the muskrats</i>
<i> will shed their valuable</i>

07:02.923 --> 07:04.823
<i> coats in the coming weeks.</i>

